Screen Scraping Examples

SICSS-Rutgers 2020

A few examples of scraping websites

This document provides a few additional scraping examples to supplement the process described in Chris Bail’s video. We recommend watching that video first.

You will need the package rvest installed on your computer

install.packages("rvest")

Load the package

library(rvest)

Example 1: Extracting a table from Wikipedia (based on Chris Bail’s video)

You will need to use the Chrome developer tools or Chrome extension SelectorGadget to identify the xpath for the appropriate place on the webpage. I always find this can take some trial and error.

## url for webpage
wikipedia <-read_html("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Health_Organization_ranking_of_health_systems_in_2000")

## use chrome developer tools and hover over area to locate relevant html piece
section_of_wikipedia <- html_node(wikipedia,
                                  xpath='//*[@id="mw-content-text"]/div/table') 

## because we want to extract the table, we can use this special function
mytable <- html_table(section_of_wikipedia)

Example 2: A similar example, extracting a table from Vary CSS

This website has a more simple structure. See if you can identify a table xpath on your own.

## url for webpage
varycss <- read_html("http://varycss.org/groups.html")

## locate the table component of the html
groups <- html_node(varycss, xpath = '/html/body/div/section/table[1]')

## extract the table
mytable2 <- html_table(groups)

Example 3: Let’s extract some text using html_text

We will extract Representative Ocasio-Cortez’s platform of issues.

aoc <- read_html("https://ocasio-cortez.house.gov/issues")
issues <- html_nodes(aoc, xpath = '//*[(@id = "block-menu-block-section-menu")]//a')

## We want just the text of the issues, so we use html_text
issuetitles <- html_text(issues)

Example 4: Kick it up a notch! Let’s extract some links, followed by text

Instead of extracting the text from the issue list, let’s extract the links using html_attr().

## We want just the links, so we will use html_attr with href
issuelinks <- html_attr(issues, 'href')

## Take a look
issuelinks[1]
## [1] "/ajs"
## Not quite the full url, so let's append these to the main url using paste()
issueurls <- paste("https://ocasio-cortez.house.gov", issuelinks, sep="")

OK, now we need to go to each url and extract the relevant text

## Let's build a dataframe for storage
aocplatform <- data.frame(issues = issuetitles, url = issueurls,
                          text = NA)

head(aocplatform)
##                    issues

## 5     https://ocasio-cortez.house.gov/issues/economic-inequality   NA
## 6               https://ocasio-cortez.house.gov/issues/education   NA

We now create a loop that 1) goes to each url, 2) extracts the main paragraph 3) stores the text in our dataframe

for(i in 1:length(issueurls)){
  page <- read_html(issueurls[i])
  ## tried this out for first page, then hoped it worked for the rest
  ## if it doesn't, may need to explore different possible structures for pages
  text <- html_node(page, xpath='//*[@id="block-system-main"]')
  aocplatform$text[i] <- html_text(text)
}
## You may still have to do some text cleaning, but we got pretty far!
aocplatform$text[1]
